3. View the test results and screenshots in the `cypress/reports` folder.

This framework provides a solid foundation for your Cypress testing needs, with the added benefit of automatic screenshot capture and reporting. Happy testing!

Here's a C++ function using a Markdown parser library called `pugcpp` to convert Markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <pugcpp/pugcpp.hpp>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_node doc = pugcpp::compiler::compile("<html><body>", "html");
    pugi::xml_node body = docFirstChild("body");
    pugi::compiler::compile(markdown, body);
    std::ostringstream oss;
    std::string html;
    doc.save_string(oss);
    html = oss.str();
    return html;
}
```

To use this function, you'll need to install the `pugcpp` library. You can do this using CMake or by downloading the source code and compiling it manually.

Here's a more complete example with error handling and formatting:

```cpp
#include <pugcpp/pugcpp.hpp>
#include <pugcpp/parser.hpp>
#include <pugcpp/compiler.hpp>
#include <pugcpp/tree.hpp>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    try {
        pugi::xml_document doc;
        pugi::xml_node root = doc.append_child(pugi::node_type::node_element, "html");
        pugi::xml_node body = root.append_child(pugi::node_type::node_element, "body");
        pugi::parser markdownParser;
        pugi::compiler compiler(body);
        if (!markdownParser.parse(markdown, compiler)) {
            throw std::runtime_error("Failed to parse Markdown");
        }
        std::ostringstream oss;
        std::string html;
        doc.save_string(oss);
        html = oss.str();
        return html;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Markdown to HTML conversion failed: " + std::string(e.what()));
    }
}
```

This function will return the HTML representation of the input Markdown string. Note that it uses `pugi` for XML parsing and compilation, and `pugcpp` for Markdown parsing.

If you prefer not to use an external library, you can implement your own Markdown parser or use a regex-based solution, but this will be much more complex and error-prone.

Here's a very basic example of a Markdown parser using regex:

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;
    // Headers
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("^# (.*)$", "<h1>$1</h1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("^## (.*)$", "<h2>$1</h2>");
    // Bold and Italic
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("__(.*)__", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<b>$1</b>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("(*.*)", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<i>$1</i>");
    // Links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("[(*)](.*)[)]", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<a href='$2'>$1</a>");
    return html;
}
```

This is a very basic example and doesn't support many Markdown features. For a more complete solution, consider using a dedicated Markdown parsing library.

What a classic! Creating a smooth, image-based Snake game in C is a challenging but rewarding project. I'll provide a high-level guide to help you get started. We'll use the SDL (Simple DirectMedia Layer) library to handle graphics, input, and game logic. We'll also use PNG images for the game assets.

**Prerequisites:**

1. Install SDL development libraries: `sudo apt-get install libsdl2-dev` (for Ubuntu-based systems) or download and install from the official SDL website.
2. Familiarize yourself with C programming and basic game development concepts.

**Game Requirements:**

* Use images for the snake, food, and background.
* Smooth animation (at least 30 FPS).
* Keyboard input for movement (arrow keys).
* Game over condition (collision with wall or self).
* Scorekeeping.

**Game Structure:**

1. **Game Loop:**
	* Initialize SDL and create a window.
	* Main game loop: render, update, and handle input.
	* Exit the loop when the game is over.
2. **Game State:**
	* `snake`: a struct representing the snake's position, direction, and length.
	* `food`: a struct representing the food's position.
	* `score`: an integer to keep track of the score.
	* `game_over`: a boolean to indicate the game state.
3. **Rendering:**
	* Load and store images for the snake, food, and background.
	* Use SDL's rendering functions (e.g., `SDL_RenderCopy`) to draw the images.
	* Clear the screen and update the display.

**Code Structure:**
```c
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <time.h>

// Define constants
#define WIDTH 640
#define HEIGHT 480
#define SNAKE_SIZE 20
#define FOOD_SIZE 10
#define FPS 30

// Game structs
typedef struct {
    int x, y; // position
    int dir; // direction (0: up, 1: right, 2: down, 3: left)
    int length; // number of segments
} Snake;

typedef struct {
    int x, y; // position
} Food;

// Game variables
Snake snake;
Food food;
int score;
bool game_over;

// Load images
SDL_Texture* snake_texture;
SDL_Texture* food_texture;
SDL_Texture* background_texture;

int main() {
    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        printf("SDL initialization failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return 1;
    }

    // Create window
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, WIDTH, HEIGHT, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    if (!window) {
        printf("Window creation failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        SDL_Quit();
        return 1;
    }

    // Create renderer
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (!renderer) {
        printf("Renderer creation failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
        SDL_Quit();
        return 1;
    }

    // Load images
    snake_texture = SDL_LoadTexture(renderer, "snake.png", NULL);
    food_texture = SDL_LoadTexture(renderer, "food.png", NULL);
    background_texture = SDL_LoadTexture(renderer, "background.png", NULL);

    // Initialize game state
    snake.x = WIDTH / 2;
    snake.y = HEIGHT / 2;
    snake.dir = 0; // initial direction: up
    snake.length = 1;
    food.x = rand() % (WIDTH - FOOD_SIZE);
    food.y = rand() % (HEIGHT - FOOD_SIZE);
    score = 0;
    game_over = false;

    // Main game loop
    while (!game_over) {
        // Handle input
        SDL_Event event;
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
                // Handle arrow key presses
                if (event.key.keysym.sym == SDLK_UP && snake.dir != 2) {
                    snake.dir = 0; // up
                } else if (event.key.keysym.sym == SDLK_RIGHT && snake.dir != 0) {
                    snake.dir = 1; // right
                } else if (event.key.keysym.sym == SDLK_DOWN && snake.dir != 0) {
                    snake.dir = 2; // down
                } else if (event.key.keysym.sym == SDLK_LEFT && snake.dir != 1) {
                    snake.dir = 3; // left
                }
            }
        }

        // Update game logic
        // ...

        // Render game
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, background_texture, NULL, NULL);
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snake_texture, NULL, &snake);
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, food_texture, NULL, &food);
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);

        // Update FPS
        SDL_Delay(1000 / FPS);
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyTexture(snake_texture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(food_texture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(background_texture);
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
}
```
**Additional Tips:**

* Use a separate thread for animation (e.g., using SDL's `SDL_CreateThread`) to avoid blocking the main thread.
* Implement collision detection for the snake and food, and update the score accordingly.
* Use a more efficient data structure for the snake's body, such as a linked list or an array of structs.
* Add sound effects and music to enhance the game experience.
* Consider using a more advanced graphics library, such as SDL2_gfx, for more features and performance.

This should give you a good starting point for creating a smooth, image-based Snake game in C using SDL. Good luck, and have fun!

